    <text>
        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC">              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-down"/><persName><gap extent="unknown" unit="stroke" reason="lost"/> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">ᚋᚐᚊᚔ</w> <name nymRef="#?">ᚅᚓ<supplied reason="lost">ᚈ</supplied><gap extent="unknown" unit="stroke" reason="lost"/>ᚐᚄ</name></persName>
                </ab> 
            </div>                    
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:up-down"/><persName><gap extent="unknown" unit="stroke" reason="lost"/> <w type="formula" lemma="maqqas">MAQI</w> <name nymRef="#?">NE<supplied reason="lost">T</supplied><gap extent="unknown" unit="stroke" reason="lost"/>AS</name></persName>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
            <note>Macalister (1945, 273) suggests that the chipped portion at the beginning of the inscription <q>must have contained a short name, spelt with H-consonants only</q>. Of the proposed letter T in Macalister's reading, only one score remains. </note>                    
                </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>The inscription likely consisted of the X son of Y formula.</p> 
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>According to Macalister (1945, 274), the <q>Waterford name <persName xml:lang="sga">Neta-Segamonas</persName> is excluded, as it would have been preceded by MUCOI</q>.</p>
            </div>
